  Unifying algebraic approach in ultralocal models   
Though the QYBE itself represents  an  unifying approach
for all ultralocal models, we     intend to specify here 
a common  algebraic  structure independent of the spectral parameter 
that will 
 not only systematize  the models including those 
listed above,
  but also identify 
 their  common integrable  origin,   
  establishing  naturally the quantum integrability 
for all of them,  simultaneously.
From  the above list of models, 
  one may observe that,  
 different   integrable 
models have  their representative  Lax operators 
 in diverse
 forms with varied  dependence on  the spectral parameter
as well as
 on the basic operators like  
  spin, bosonic  or
the canonical  operators. However 
the -matrices  associated with
all of them 
 are given by  the
 same   form (R-mat ) with known trigonometric (trm ) or 
its limiting rational (rrm ) solutions. 
To explain this  intriguing  observation 
we may look for a common origin for the Lax operators
linked with a general 
underlying algebra free from spectral parameters, though derivable 
 from the QYBE.
 We propose to take the  Lax operator of such   ancestor
model   in the form kunprl99 
L_trig ^(anc) ()  = (     ),  i  ,  _=2 ^1 , nlslq2  where  and  are some operators, the algebraic 
 properties of 
which are specified below. The 
structure of (nlslq2 )  becomes  clearer if we notice
the decomposition 
, where  are 
spectral parameter -independent upper and
lower triangular  matrices similar to the construction of frt .
 Inserting (nlslq2 ) in QYBE  together with its associated 
 -matrix (R-mat ) with  trigonometric solution  (trm )
 and matching different powers of the
  we obtain the underlying general algebra
as
 [S^3,S^ ] = S^  ,    [ S^ + , S^-  ] =
 ( M^+(2 S^3) + M^-   ( 2 S^3  ) )1  , [M^, ]=0,
nlslq2a with  
 behaving as central elements with arbitrary values of
's.  As we have mentioned above, the integrable systems are associated
 with an important  Hopf algebra ,
 exhibiting the
properties like  
1) coproduct   , 2) antipode  or
'inverse' ,
3) counit     4)  
multiplication 
  and  5) unit  
. It can  be shown that all these properties   hold also  for     
(nlslq2a ) defining it 
 as a  
Hopf algebra. Referring the interested readers to the original works
qa  for more mathematical
treatment  of
 the noncocommutative Hopf algebra, we give here only some  
simple and
intuitive  arguments in its
constructions. For example  
 the coproduct , the most important of these 
characteristics, can be derived for algebra (nlslq2a ) 
by  exploiting    a    QYBE   property  that
  the  product of
two Lax operators   is again 
a  solution of the  QYBE and may be given in the explicit form
as
