Fundamental and regular models 
The Lax operator  in general
 acts on the product space , of  the common auxiliary
space   and   the quantum space  at site . The models 
with     isomorphic to all
  and given by the fundamental representation
 are called fundamental  models.
  For such models the finite-dimensional  matrix representations of  
   auxiliary and  quantum spaces  
 become equivalent  and  may lead to  
  
 However
for clarifying a misconception  
prevelant in the literature,
 we should stress that  a model is 
 represented  by its Lax operator only,  
the associated
 -matrix accounts for the commutation property of the elements
of this  Lax operator
through QYBE. Therefore  even for a fundamental model the Lax
operator may differ from its -matrix. 
 We may however demand for the fundamental models
 an useful additional 
property:
, known as the regularity  condition 
 given through the permutation operator, which may be
 expressed  in the general case 
 as a  matrix 
 
 being a matrix with its  element  
as  and the rest .

Recall that  the global operator  is constructed
from the local Lax operators   as  




where the transfer matrix 
 acts on the total quantum space 

 
Therefore, from the knowledge of Lax operators it is possible to derive
all conserved quantities including the Hamiltonian, which  in
general would be nonlocal objects.  The above
  regularity condition on 
  Lax operators however allows to  overcome this difficulty
and obtain Hamiltonians with  nearest-neibour (NN) interactions.
Let us pay  some special attention to this 
 specific  group of models
since,
 as we will see below, the most  
important integrable models applicable to condensed matter physics
 related problems
are given by the regular models with  etc.
For this reason,
 though   our main concern in this paper is
  auxiliary matrix space,  we describe here 
more general  cases and demonstrate that Hamiltonians 
  of such different physical models   interestingly  have similar 
 forms,
 when expressed through 
the permutation operator . Such a permutation operator
  exhibits  space  interchanging
 property 
,  along with      and .
For all regular and periodic 
 models,  using the freedom of cyclic rotation of matrices under the 
trace, we can express  the transfer matrix  as
