Fusion method 
We have constructed  spin, boson as well as the q-spin and q-boson  
  models through realization
of particular  Lax operators with inequivalent auxiliary and quantum spaces.
However in case of  finite-dimensional higher rank  spin representations 
there exists an intriguing method, known as the fusion method ,
 for obtaining higher  spin
models by  fusing  the elementary -matrices like (R-mat ).
 Thus by  fusion of only the quantum spaces one  can construct 
spin-s Lax operators with a spin- auxiliary space, as obtainable 
also directly from  (nlslq2 ) as a particular realization.
   Fusing further the
auxiliary spaces 
 the higher-spin  Lax operator with spin-s  auxiliary space may be
constructed as
L_ab  =(P^+_a  P^+_b  )
 _j=1 ^s _k=1 ^s R_a_jb_k (+i(2s-k-j))(P^+_a   P^+_b  ) g_2s () fuse  with   as
 the symmetrizer in the fused spin-s space 
 and   some normalizing factor babus .
For the rational -matrix corresponding to  (rrm ) one obtains from 
(fuse )
  the 
 integrable spin-s
 Babujian-Takhtajan  model babus , which for  may be
 given in the same form as  Hamiltonian (s1 ), but with .
Similarly for the trigonometric case (trm ) the fused model would
correspond to integrable anisotropic higher-spin chain.

It may however be stressed that  such 
fusion technique, as far as we know,
 has not been formulated yet for  
   bosonic and q-bosonic models. Such extension , at least for
the restricted values of , needs therefore more attention.
 Construction of classical models 
The  systematic  procedure   for constructing  quantum integrable models 
as various reductions of the same ancestor model,  
as described here, is applicable naturally also 
  to the corresponding classical models by taking the
 classical limit . At this limit all 
 field operators would be transformed
to ordinary functions with their commutators reducing to the Poisson
brackets.  Note also that parameter  appearing in  
 the -matrix   is   scaled actually as 
 , which  
yields the  classical -matrix: 
 and reduces  QYBE (ybe ) 
 to its classical limit 


.
The  classical   Lax operator reduced from (nlslq2 ) 
 would remain
however  almost in  the same form, though 
 the corresponding quantum algebras would change    
 into their corresponding  Poisson algebras.
This aspect of classical integrable systems is given in great detail in the
excellent monograph Hamil-ft .
 Using  these  classical analogs of quantum systems 
 one can   therefore apply the   algebraic 
 scheme  formulated above for  generating
  quantum  models also in classical context
and construct systematically 
the corresponding classical integrable models classm .

Integrable statistical systems: vertex models 
-dimensional quantum systems are  known to be related to -dimensional
classical statistical models, which is true   naturally also
 for , where the  integrability of models might get manifested.
Interestingly, integrable quantum spin chain
and the corresponding  vertex model
 share  the same quantum -matrix and  have  the same  
 representation for the transfer matrix,   
  commutativity of which:    
 guarantees their integrability.
However, while the  spin chain
Hamiltonian   is expressed through the transfer
 matrix  as ,  the partition
function 
 of the  vertex model is constructed from   as 
. 
The known integrable  vertex models are usually related to the
quantum fundamental  models described above. 


In conventional   vertex models 
 each bond connecting  arrays in a 
2-dimensional lattice  can take  different possible random  values 
with certain probabilities, which
 for a
 configuration  of bonds  meeting at each vertex point
 is  given by the Boltzmann weights
.
These Boltzmann weights may be assigned as matrix elements 

 of a -matrix (though 
 it might be of a more general -operator,
as we will see below), which for integrable models must
satisfy the Yang-Baxter equation (ybe ) and correspond   to 
 a  quantum integrable model.
The  partition function  of these vertex models may be    expressed  as 
 


The  simplest    among the vertex models  for  
is the 6-vertex model 
 baxter ,  which corresponds to the  spin chain 
 and may be 
 defined on a square lattice with a random direction on
 each bond ( left or  right on the horizontal, up or down on the vertical), 
constrained by the ice rule ,
 that the number of incoming and outgoing arrows at each vertex are the
same. This leaves only  possible configurations and the corresponding 
 Boltzmann weights may be given by  nontrivial matrix elements 
of the -matrix (R-mat ) with (trm ). 
 It is fascinating that this model may
describe the possible 
configurations of Hydrogen (H) ions around Oxygen (O) atoms in an ice
crystal having
 two  different (close-removed ) positions of the
H-ions relative to the O-atom in the H-bonding, while the ice rule
corresponds to the charge neutrality of the water molecule.

 A more  general  6-vertex model  may be obtained if instead we assign
its Boltzmann weights  directly to the spin- matrix
representation of the general ancestor 
Lax operator (nlslq2 ).  The 
 parameters 
 present in the Lax operator may be combined to serve  as the  
 horizontal  and vertical 
 fields acting on the model, which
   recovers amazingly the
most general 6-vertex model   proposed many years ago 
  yys  through a  different construction. This also confirms the fact
that the Lax operator 
 (nlslq2 ) is indeed in the core of integrable quantum as
well as statistical models. 
 Using twisting  transformation  one can recover also  the  
  vertex model introduced in wadati . 



We may consider higher vertex models with , which may be obtained 
from the -matrix (or the Lax operators) of the corresponding 
quantum integrable fundamental models with higher-dimensional auxiliary
spaces.
The well known examples are
the -vertex model 19v  related to the
 Babujian-Takhtajan integrable spin-1 model 
babus , the Boltzmann weights of which 
may be given by the matrix elements of  Lax operator
 (fuse ) with . Similarly one may construct   the 
vertex models
  equivalent  to the Hubbard model,
  supersymmetric t-J model, 
 Bariev chain etc. 
 vertex .

In a following section
  new type of vertex models will be constructed 
from  our ancestor Lax operator using
 nonfundamental representations.


Directions for constructing new classes of ultralocal models 
 The same unified  scheme described in sect. 3 for 
constructing  integrable models
may be used also to indicate  various directions for  generating new 
integrable classes  
of quantum and statistical  models.

Inhomogeneous  models 
In all 
above constructions  the central elements
in  the ancestor models 
() or   
(LK ) are chosen  as constant parameters. However 
if they are chosen  as  site dependent (or may even time dependent)
functions we can get an inhomogeneous  class of models.
In these cases  the 's 
would be  attached with site indices  as s in the Lax operators and similarly 
 in  (g )  would appear as 
 functions, leading to the corresponding 
 inhomogeneous extensions of the known integrable
  models, namely  inhomogeneous lattice sine-Gordon,
Liouville, Toda chain, NLS model etc.
 However
since the local algebra remains  same as the original model, 
they have the same quantum
-matrices.
Though similar inhomogeneous Toda chain, NLS models etc.  were proposed
earlier as classical systems, they seem to be
 new and yet unstudied as quantum models.  Recall 
that  the  impurity models proposed earlier impure 
 fall into this class and 
are obtained by a particular choice of inhomogeneous 's
which amounts to a shifting of the  
spectral parameter. Implementing the same idea to 
  the  spin chain we notice that, if  in its constructing  
along with  we choose   resulting again 
 , we get the same  
 form of the Lax operator, but with a shift ,
resulting  that of the Gaudin model (gaud ). Similarly higher spin
representations
as well as   
variant  would yield  other generalizations  of the 
  same model.  The commuting set of
Hamiltonians for the Gaudin model  may be  
 generated from its transfer matrix  at the limit  gaudin  as  

. Remarkably, the  Gaudin model may be mapped into
the  integrable BSC model, which is of immense contemporary interest
 angela .
  
 Physically such inhomogeneities may be interpreted as 
impurities, varying  external fields,  incommensuration etc.

Hybrid models 

Another way of 
constructing  new  models  
 is to  use different realizations of
 algebras () or () at different
lattice sites,
depending on the type of the -matrix.
For example  one may  consider spin- and spin-1
representations of   at alternate lattice sites, which 
was  realized  actually in alternates .
 However we can  build   more general inhomogeneous
 integrable models by considering 
  different
underlying algebras and  different Lax operators at differing sites.
The basic idea is that the Lax operators representing  different models that
 are descended from the same
ancestor model 
and  share the same -matrix can be combined together to build 
various hybrid models preserving quantum integrability.
For example,
we may consider  fermion-boson or spin-boson interacting models by inserting
alternatively spin- and bosonic (or q-bosonic) Lax operators at
alternate sites. One of such  physical constructions would be the celebrated
Jaynes-Cummings model.  
 It is  possible also  to construct some exotic hybrid integrable 
models, an example of which could be
 a  hybrid  sine-Gordon-Liouville model, where for 
 it would follow
the sine-Gordon dynamics, while for  the Liouville dynamics!
   



Nonfundamental statistical models 
Vertex models, as mentioned, are   described  generally 
by the  -matrix of a
regular quantum integrable model.
 However 
one can  construct 
a new class of integrable vertex models by exploiting 
a richer variety of nonfundamental 
 systems, where we  
 define the Boltzmann weights as  matrix  elements of the 
generalized   Lax operator (nlslq2 ): 
 ,  with the 
use of  the explicit matrix representation for the basic operators
 as
  <s,mS^3m,s>=m _m,m ,  <s,mS^m,s>
= f^_s(m)_m1,m  .qsrep 

 Here  is defined as in (g ).
 Such general
 Boltzmann weights would now represent an ancestor  vertex model
  analogous to the quantum case and would  generate 
 through various reductions   new series of  vertex  models, 
 linked to
 q-spin and q-boson with generic q, q roots of unity and 
 kuna02 .
 In all these models, generalizing the usual approach
 the horizontal (h)  and vertical (v) links 
may  become  inequivalent and independent  at every vertex point.  
 The h links, which are related to the auxiliary space    admit
 2 values, while 
 the v links, which correspond to the  quantum space  may  have
richer  possibilities with ,
   being the dimension of 
the nonfundamental  matrix-representation of the  q-algebras.
The familiar ice-rule is generalized here as the 'color' conservation 
  for determining nonzero  Boltzmann weights.
Note that, alternatively finite-dimensional higher 
spin and -spin vertex models
 can also be constructed  using the
 fusion  technique babus .


An interesting   possibility of regulating dimension  for the matrix
representation opens up at
, when a
  variety of new q-spin and q-boson vertex models with finite-dimensional
representation  can be generated kuna02 .


As in quantum models we can also construct here  
 a rich collection of  hybrid models  by combining different
 vertex models of the same class and inserting 
their defining  Boltzmann weights
along the vertex points  in each row,
 in any but in the same  manner. 
Due to the  association 
with the same -matrix the integrability of such statistical
models is naturally  preserved.

  Unified   Bethe ansatz solution 
In physical models our  aim  usually is to solve the eigenvalue problem  
for the Hamiltonian only.  
Solvable models allow such   exact solutions  
 through
coordinate formulation of the Bethe ansatz (CBA)  bethe31 , which
 was used successfully in many  condensed matter
physics related problems like spin-chain, attractive and repulsive 
-Bose gas, Hubbard model etc condmat .
 Nevertheless CBA depends heavily on the structure 
of the Hamiltonian  of individual models and lacks consequently 
  the unified approach
of its algebraic formulation. 
We would  focus here 
 briefly only  on the   algebraic Bethe ansatz (ABA)  
 aba,korbook , which  under certain conditions can solve
 the  eigenvalue problem 
for the spectral parameter-dependent transfer matrix 



 and hence through its expansion  the eigenvalue problem for the whole
  set of conserved  operators, simultaneously.
Moreover, the ABA due to its predominantly
 model-independent features, which we will demonstrate below, 
appears to be a fairly   universal method.

Since the eigenvectors are common for all commuting conserved operators,
 by   expanding 
 simply as
  c_1 m>= 
  _m'(0)_m^-1 (0)m>
,  c_2 m>= 
  (_m'(0)_m^-1 (0))'m>
evpcn etc. we obtain their   respective values,
 where   one may take  or other combinations of 
's as the Hamiltonian, depending on the concrete  model.
This  powerful   method applicable to both  integrable   
   quantum and statistical  systems
requires however
 explicit 
knowledge of the associated Lax operator and 
 the -matrix.


It  may be noticed that the off -diagonal element  ()
of the monodromy matrix (monod ) acts generally 
 like  creation (annihilation) operator for the pseudoparticles,
 induced by the local
creation (annihilation) operator as the matrix elements in 
  acting on the quantum space at . Therefore
the -particle state  may be  created 
by  acting  times with  on the pseudovacuum 
 , giving
 

, where we suppose the crucial annihilation condition .


Now for solving the eigenvalue problem of  
 exactly, we have to drag this operator
 through the string of 's without spoiling their structure 
and  finally hit the 
pseudovacuum giving 
 and 

.
 For this purpose therefore one  requires 
  commutation  relations between the
elements  of (monod ), which  for ultralocal models  may be derived 
from the QYBE (gybe ). This, apart from  ensuring the  integrability
 of the system, is another 
important role played by  (gybe ),
 yielding 
the relations
