the  Boltzmann weights  as



.
It is  remarkable that 
  the rest of the  terms in  (lambda ) and (be ) 
are  given solely through the -matrix elements 
  and therefore depend only on
 the related class  (trm ) or (rrm ).
Recall that in  integrable  models, as described in sect. 3, 
the -matrix remains same for all models belonging to a particular class,
while   the -operators differ and  may be obtained 
 through various reductions from the
same ancestor Lax operator.

 Therefore  taking
the Lax operator elements in (lambda ) and (be ) as  
  those from the general Lax operator (), one may   consider  
the above  eigenvalue   and the Bethe equation  to be
 the unifying equations for      exact solution of 
all   integrable ultralocal
quantum and  statistical models 
constructed here.
Consequently models like the DNLS, SG, Liouville
and the  chain together with the 6-vertex model,
 belonging to the trigonometric
 class (trm )  should share  similar  
eigenvalue relations with individual differences appearing only in 
the   form of   and  coefficients.
Thus  
this  deep rooted
 universality  in integrable systems  helps to solve the eigenvalue
problem for the whole class of models and for the full  hierarchy of
their 
conserved currents in a systematic way. 
